In [6]:
plt.figure(figsize=(12, 10))

star_counts = df["stars"].value_counts().sort_index()

plt.bar(star_counts.index, star_counts.values, color='green')
plt.xlabel("Ratings")
plt.ylabel("Number of reviews")
plt.title("Each ratings' count")
plt.xticks(star_counts.index)

plt.show()

From the above bar char we can conclude that majority of reviews rated only for 1 star, while the least part put 6 stars

In [9]:
mean_rating_by_country = df.groupby("country")["stars"].mean().sort_values()

plt.figure(figsize=(12, 10))
colors = plt.cm.cividis_r(range(len(mean_rating_by_country)))

mean_rating_by_country.plot(kind="bar", color=colors)
plt.xlabel("Countries")
plt.ylabel("Mean Rating")
plt.title("Mean rating by Country")
plt.xticks(rotation=90)

plt.show()

The average number of stars varies greatly between different nations; it can be as high as 10, indicating high levels of contentment, or as low as 1, indicating far lower levels of satisfaction. The country with the highest number of reviews shares an average rating of about 4, which indicates a moderate degree of satisfaction in relation to other countries.

In [14]:
word_list = reviews.split()

stopwords = text.ENGLISH_STOP_WORDS.union(["The", "British", "London", "Airways", "Verified", "Heathrow", "flight", "I", "ba", "passenger","u", "london", "airway", "", "We", "Review", "british", "airline", "airways", "-", "BA", "heathrow","plane","lhr","review"])
new_list = [i for i in word_list if i not in stopwords]

#top 10 most common words
most_common_words = FreqDist(new_list).most_common(10)
word_dict = pd.Series(dict(most_common_words))

word_plot = sns.barplot(x=word_dict.index, y=word_dict.values)
word_plot.bar_label(word_plot.containers[0])
plt.xticks(rotation=30)
